245
00:17:03,557 --> 00:17:08,458
The INR concluded late last year that
these tubes are probably for artillery use.

246
00:17:08,353 --> 00:17:12,003
The DOE agreed they exactly matched
those used by Iraq for artillery rockets.

247
00:17:11,899 --> 00:17:13,254
Where are the tubes?

248
00:17:13,359 --> 00:17:14,610
WINPAC has them.

249
00:17:15,236 --> 00:17:16,487
We've examined them.

250
00:17:16,800 --> 00:17:20,658
And this is my point.
None of you guys have even seen the tubes.

251
00:17:22,535 --> 00:17:23,995
I've seen them.

252
00:17:25,351 --> 00:17:27,124
And when was that?

253
00:17:27,019 --> 00:17:30,356
When I led the covert team
that intercepted them in Jordan,

254
00:17:30,356 --> 00:17:33,589
brought back samples,
and delivered them to you guys at WINPAC.

255
00:17:34,527 --> 00:17:37,968
And I take it you're not a nuclear expert.

256
00:17:39,220 --> 00:17:42,557
These tubes are a match

257
00:17:42,557 --> 00:17:46,728
for those designed by German scientist
Gernot Zippe in the '50s.

258
00:17:46,624 --> 00:17:49,126
You're right. I'm no nuclear expert

259
00:17:49,126 --> 00:17:54,236
but Dr. Houston Wood at
the University of Virginia Atomic Facility is.

260
00:17:55,174 --> 00:18:01,014
He also knows Dr. Zippe and he told him
that the wall thickness of the Iraqi tubes

261
00:18:00,806 --> 00:18:03,830
was 3 or 4 times the thickness
of his design.

262
00:18:04,247 --> 00:18:08,939
Right, and he also said that the length
of the tubes is twice that of Zippe's design.

263
00:18:08,835 --> 00:18:11,338
In fact, he said that the only thing
that was similar

264
00:18:11,338 --> 00:18:14,049
between his tubes and the aluminum tubes

265
00:18:14,049 --> 00:18:15,926
was that they were both made of aluminum.

266
00:18:15,822 --> 00:18:20,618
A metal that hasn't been used
in gas centrifuges since 1952.

267
00:18:21,140 --> 00:18:25,937
I went to Vienna. Okay? Canada.
And I've been working on this for months.

268
00:18:25,832 --> 00:18:28,231
There are centrifuges. Fact.

269
00:18:28,231 --> 00:18:31,255
So, basically, they're your tubes

270
00:18:31,255 --> 00:18:33,966
and if we don't let you win,
you're taking them home.

271
00:18:35,009 --> 00:18:36,156
That's pathetic.

272
00:18:36,677 --> 00:18:38,867
Joe, no one's saying you're wrong here,

273
00:18:38,867 --> 00:18:42,726
but if you're right, it's huge,
so, we ask the question.

274
00:18:43,664 --> 00:18:46,480
Right? We have to ask the question.

275
00:18:54,300 --> 00:18:57,012
Niger has two uranium mines
in the Sahara desert.

276
00:18:57,637 --> 00:18:58,680
One is flooded.

277
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:01,079
The other is run by COGEMA,
a French subsidiary

278
00:19:01,079 --> 00:19:03,164
jointly controlled
by the Japanese and Germans.

279
00:19:03,686 --> 00:19:07,857
Five hundred tons of yellowcake
is not an off-the-books size transaction.

280
00:19:07,857 --> 00:19:13,071
It represents a 40% production increase
in the nation's annual output of uranium.

281
00:19:12,862 --> 00:19:15,782
A sale that size
would leave a huge paper trail.

282
00:19:17,137 --> 00:19:21,204
Any documentation would, by law,
have to be signed by the Prime Minister,

283
00:19:21,934 --> 00:19:24,020
Foreign Minister, and the Minister of Mines.

284
00:19:24,437 --> 00:19:26,210
But say it was an off-the-books deal.

285
00:19:26,210 --> 00:19:29,755
How do you hide the transportation
of 500 tons of anything,

286
00:19:29,651 --> 00:19:32,049
let alone lightly-refined uranium?

287
00:19:32,049 --> 00:19:36,533
You're talking 50 semi-tractor trucks
on one road through villages

288
00:19:36,429 --> 00:19:39,975
where nothing passed for months
except maybe one bush taxi.

289
00:19:39,766 --> 00:19:41,852
It would be the biggest event for months.

290
00:19:41,852 --> 00:19:45,606
To say they forgot
is like kids forgetting Christmas.

291
00:19:46,440 --> 00:19:48,317
You have the droughts of the '70s and '80s

292
00:19:48,317 --> 00:19:52,384
which brought millions of dollars
in US aid which continues today.

293
00:19:52,697 --> 00:19:56,659
It doesn't make any sense that the Nigerians
would compromise that lifeline.

294
00:19:56,451 --> 00:20:00,622
For that reason and for all the reasons
that I've been telling you,

295
00:20:01,873 --> 00:20:04,793
it is my opinion that this sale
could not have happened.

296
00:20:08,964 --> 00:20:11,258
So, what happens next?

297
00:20:12,197 --> 00:20:15,742
Well, they write a report,
give it to the analysts.

298
00:20:15,742 --> 00:20:20,018
It will be rewritten, then kicked upstairs
and combined with other reports they get.

299
00:20:20,747 --> 00:20:21,895
What?

300
00:20:21,999 --> 00:20:25,336
I just think it's ludicrous that they're gonna
send somebody all the way over there

301
00:20:25,336 --> 00:20:27,734
and spend all that money
for the same conclusion.

302
00:20:27,630 --> 00:20:31,592
You can't compile intelligence
from a single source.

303
00:20:31,384 --> 00:20:33,782
That's not intelligence. That's an opinion.

304
00:20:33,678 --> 00:20:35,555
Trust me. It's a fact.

305
00:20:36,598 --> 00:20:38,475
- Says who?
- Says me.

306
00:20:38,371 --> 00:20:41,707
You're just a teeny-weeny tiny cog
in a giant machine.

307
00:20:42,750 --> 00:20:45,253
You did your job. You should feel good.

308
00:20:45,253 --> 00:20:48,068
They count on that.
That's why they don't pay you.

309
00:20:50,154 --> 00:20:52,761
I'm not feeling very 007-ish.

310
00:20:54,638 --> 00:20:57,141
Maybe I can get the kids
to make a medal for you.

311
00:20:59,852 --> 00:21:02,772
Us 00s prefer gratuitous sex.

312
00:21:13,617 --> 00:21:17,371
Maybe I can do something about that.

313
00:21:22,376 --> 00:21:24,983
Angola's holding another round of bidding

314
00:21:24,983 --> 00:21:28,737
on their deep-water offshore blocks
at the end of the year.

315
00:21:29,050 --> 00:21:32,074
Chevron, Elf, and Exxon are interested.

316
00:22:04,609 --> 00:22:06,486
- She did it!
- No, I didn't!

317
00:22:06,486 --> 00:22:08,572
Okay. Everybody okay?

318
00:22:08,572 --> 00:22:10,970
Four arms, four legs. No broken bones.

319
00:22:10,970 --> 00:22:13,264
Hey, kids.
Mr. Wilson, I'm so sorry I'm late.

320
00:22:13,264 --> 00:22:16,184
- That's fine. Look, guys, Kim's here.
- When's Mommy coming home?

321
00:22:20,042 --> 00:22:23,379
It's an honor
to meet you at last, Dr. Harper.

322
00:22:23,379 --> 00:22:27,967
I was unable to attend
your string gravity seminar at MIT

323
00:22:27,759 --> 00:22:30,574
but I read a transcript.

324
00:22:30,991 --> 00:22:33,390
Did you read my latest paper on quarks?

325
00:22:34,016 --> 00:22:38,708
Dr. Harper, I cite your 1995 essay
more than once.

326
00:22:40,898 --> 00:22:44,131
Dr. Harper's in Cambridge, Massachusetts.

327
00:22:43,922 --> 00:22:48,927
She received a call yesterday
requesting she stay home for 48 hours.

328
00:22:50,179 --> 00:22:51,743
I don't understand.

329
00:22:54,767 --> 00:22:55,810
Who are you?

330
00:22:56,853 --> 00:23:01,649
I'm sorry for misleading you
but I'm here to ask you the same question,

331
00:23:03,109 --> 00:23:08,949
because you're not Professor Badawi.
Your name is Dr. Harif Al Fallari.

332
00:23:08,740 --> 00:23:10,722
You were born in Basra.

333
00:23:10,722 --> 00:23:13,329
You were lead engineer
at the Osirak nuclear facility

334
00:23:13,329 --> 00:23:16,040
until you fled Iraq and arrived here,
in Cairo.

335
00:23:17,187 --> 00:23:20,837
I need names of your colleagues
in the weapons programs.

336
00:23:21,671 --> 00:23:25,425
The lives of hundreds of thousands
of your people may depend upon it.

337
00:23:25,216 --> 00:23:27,093
This is absurd.

338
00:23:27,198 --> 00:23:29,805
You were never tortured? Broken?

339
00:23:29,700 --> 00:23:32,933
You didn't finally escape
and arrive here in Cairo with nothing?

340
00:23:35,957 --> 00:23:40,128
No. My name is Bakkar Abdel Badawi.

341
00:23:41,067 --> 00:23:44,299
I've never been to Basra. I'm a teacher.

342
00:23:48,783 --> 00:23:51,182
Dr. Fallari had two daughters.

343
00:23:53,372 --> 00:23:57,334
They were taken by Uday Hussein's
private guard.

344
00:23:57,126 --> 00:23:59,211
They were never seen again.

345
00:24:12,142 --> 00:24:15,687
I need names of your colleagues
in the weapons programs.

346
00:24:53,540 --> 00:24:55,105
Why is the OVP here?

347
00:24:56,669 --> 00:24:57,816
What?

348
00:25:03,968 --> 00:25:05,741
Yeah?

349
00:25:05,950 --> 00:25:07,514
The Vice President's men are here.

350
00:25:08,557 --> 00:25:09,704
What?

351
00:25:12,102 --> 00:25:17,003
My name is Scooter Libby.
I am the Chief of Staff to the Vice President.

352
00:25:18,984 --> 00:25:20,027
You are?

353
00:25:21,174 --> 00:25:25,971
Dave. I'm an analyst in Non-Proliferation.

354
00:25:28,578 --> 00:25:31,811
What can you tell the Vice President
about aluminum tubes?

355
00:25:32,436 --> 00:25:35,148
I didn't realize that was
what we were gonna be talking about here.

356
00:25:38,172 --> 00:25:40,466
Relax, will you?
The Veep's just dotting the I's.

357
00:25:40,466 --> 00:25:41,509
Come on, Jim.

358
00:25:41,613 --> 00:25:43,907
The only time the Vice President
comes to Langley is to cut a ribbon.

359
00:25:43,907 --> 00:25:45,054
Cheney doesn't trust us.

360
00:25:45,158 --> 00:25:47,557
This shit with Dick goes back 30 years.
It will blow over.

361
00:25:48,182 --> 00:25:50,268
Hey, Val, where are we on Iraq?

362
00:25:51,206 --> 00:25:54,022
We need to find sources
that we can rely on.

363
00:25:55,378 --> 00:25:56,942
We need to get in close.

364
00:25:57,463 --> 00:26:00,696
Jim, Val thinks she can get us
inside the weapons program.

365
00:26:02,781 --> 00:26:03,824
How?

366
00:26:06,327 --> 00:26:08,308
In three weeks
you have to come back again, okay?

367
00:26:08,204 --> 00:26:09,351
Thank you for everything.

368
00:26:12,166 --> 00:26:14,252
Sorry, there's nothing I can do.

369
00:26:15,921 --> 00:26:16,963
God bless.

370
00:26:18,945 --> 00:26:19,987
Come on.

371
00:26:21,656 --> 00:26:22,803
I said, come on!

372
00:26:33,335 --> 00:26:36,463
Dr. Hassan,
is there somewhere we could talk?

373
00:26:38,236 --> 00:26:40,426
How long is it since you saw your brother?

374
00:26:42,616 --> 00:26:43,867
1992.

375
00:26:44,597 --> 00:26:48,560
Before that, in '83, he came here
for an engineering conference.

376
00:26:48,455 --> 00:26:52,731
Twice in 25 years.
We try to stay in contact. It's difficult.

377
00:26:54,921 --> 00:26:56,485
Would you like to go back and see him?

378
00:26:59,822 --> 00:27:01,803
You want me to become a spy?

379
00:27:02,742 --> 00:27:05,870
We need to ask Hammad some questions.

380
00:27:05,870 --> 00:27:09,520
- Do you think he'd answer...
- I am a doctor. I work hard.

381
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:13,170
I'm also a mother.
I have a small daughter and I'm all she has.

382
00:27:14,212 --> 00:27:18,696
We could help your brother.
Right now he's extremely valuable to us.

383
00:27:18,592 --> 00:27:22,242
And to Saddam.
The Mukhabarat watch him night and day.

384
00:27:24,640 --> 00:27:25,996
He could come here.

385
00:27:27,039 --> 00:27:29,541
He's an expert physicist. He'd have a job.

386
00:27:30,480 --> 00:27:32,878
His children, his family would be safe.

387
00:27:32,878 --> 00:27:35,589
You, your daughter could see him
whenever you want.

388
00:27:37,258 --> 00:27:38,926
Can you help us?

389
00:27:39,135 --> 00:27:41,638
I will not do anything to help you.
I don't know you.

390
00:27:41,638 --> 00:27:43,515
If you care about Iraq, about your country...

391
00:27:43,410 --> 00:27:44,974
My country is America now.

392
00:27:46,122 --> 00:27:49,041
- Trust me, if there was another way...
- I don't trust you.

393
00:27:49,146 --> 00:27:50,710
I don't trust you at all.

394
00:27:54,881 --> 00:27:59,261
We're going to war. And your brother's
gonna be right in the middle of it.

395
00:28:08,229 --> 00:28:11,357
If the Iraqi regime wishes peace

396
00:28:11,357 --> 00:28:15,320
it will immediately
and unconditionally forswear,

397
00:28:15,320 --> 00:28:19,386
disclose and remove or destroy
all weapons of mass destruction.

398
00:28:19,595 --> 00:28:21,576
- Come in.
- They're back.

399
00:28:21,472 --> 00:28:24,496
If Iraq's regime defies us again,

400
00:28:25,226 --> 00:28:29,814
the world must move deliberately
and decisively to hold Iraq to account.

401
00:28:34,507 --> 00:28:35,862
Don't make jokes.

402
00:28:51,817 --> 00:28:54,007
He thinks I don't understand
how serious it is?

403
00:28:55,571 --> 00:29:00,472
Weeks and weeks of 15-hour days.
We've been back over this and over this.

404
00:29:02,558 --> 00:29:04,435
All right, that's it. I'm going to handle this.

405
00:29:06,520 --> 00:29:09,440
We've been over this data with you
five, six times now.

406
00:29:09,857 --> 00:29:12,464
And we don't know
how you want us to play this.

407
00:29:16,218 --> 00:29:20,494
Let me level with you here, Paul.
I don't know what these tubes are for.

408
00:29:21,224 --> 00:29:24,561
There could be something to this,
from everything you're saying

409
00:29:24,561 --> 00:29:26,229
- but very likely not, right?
- Exactly.

410
00:29:26,438 --> 00:29:28,210
Let me ask a question.

411
00:29:28,210 --> 00:29:31,339
When you say,
"We don't really know how to play this,"

412
00:29:31,339 --> 00:29:32,381
what do you mean?

413
00:29:32,903 --> 00:29:34,884
I mean to say that I don't know
how to say it any other way...

414
00:29:34,884 --> 00:29:36,448
You didn't say "I," you said "we."

415
00:29:37,283 --> 00:29:40,202
So, you and the others had discussed
how to play these briefings.

416
00:29:40,202 --> 00:29:43,226
Why does the CIA
feel the need to play these briefings?

417
00:29:43,122 --> 00:29:46,042
No, what I mean is,
I didn't mean what I just said.

418
00:29:46,042 --> 00:29:48,649
Which part? The last part?
Or other things, too?

419
00:29:48,649 --> 00:29:50,526
I'm sorry. I'm getting a little confused.

420
00:29:50,422 --> 00:29:52,299
- Do you want me to come back?
- No. God, no.

421
00:29:53,029 --> 00:29:56,053
- You don't know why I'm here, do you?
- No.

422
00:29:55,948 --> 00:30:01,267
In 1991, the United States invaded Iraq,
and afterwards weapons inspectors

423
00:30:01,162 --> 00:30:04,812
discovered Saddam was six months off
enriching uranium

424
00:30:04,604 --> 00:30:08,670
to sufficiently high specifications
to make a nuclear bomb.

425
00:30:09,192 --> 00:30:11,486
He had fissile material.

426
00:30:12,529 --> 00:30:17,117
Not a single person in the CIA
had the slightest clue

427
00:30:17,013 --> 00:30:19,620
that such a program even existed.

428
00:30:21,288 --> 00:30:26,502
So, now, one decade on are you telling me

429
00:30:26,398 --> 00:30:32,237
that you're 100% sure these tubes are not
intended to create nuclear weapons?

430
00:30:32,029 --> 00:30:34,844
One point about intelligence,
nothing is 100%.

431
00:30:34,740 --> 00:30:37,451
So, what, are you 99% sure? 98%?

432
00:30:37,451 --> 00:30:39,328
I'm saying that you can't
put an exact figure on it.

433
00:30:39,224 --> 00:30:41,518
- I'm saying that...
- But if you had to say?

434
00:30:41,518 --> 00:30:43,500
You cannot be that precise.

435
00:30:43,500 --> 00:30:45,168
Could you say you're 97% sure?

436
00:30:45,585 --> 00:30:47,775
Is there a 3% chance you've got this wrong?

437
00:30:49,026 --> 00:30:50,903
Or four or five?

438
00:30:52,155 --> 00:30:54,449
Still pretty good odds.
Do you like those odds, Paul?

439
00:30:54,970 --> 00:30:58,516
Are you willing to put your name to that?
Ready to make that call?

440
00:30:58,411 --> 00:31:01,540
- I don't make that call, sir.
- Yes, you do, Paul.

441
00:31:02,583 --> 00:31:05,398
Each time you interpret a piece of data.

442
00:31:05,919 --> 00:31:09,361
Each time you choose
a maybe over a perhaps

443
00:31:09,361 --> 00:31:12,385
you make a call, a decision.

444
00:31:12,385 --> 00:31:17,077
Right now you're making a lot of little
decisions adding up to a big decision.

445
00:31:18,016 --> 00:31:21,040
But what if there's only
a 1% chance that you're wrong?

446
00:31:21,040 --> 00:31:23,438
Can you say for sure
that you'll take that chance

447
00:31:23,438 --> 00:31:25,628
and state as a fact

448
00:31:25,628 --> 00:31:29,591
that this equipment is not intended
for a nuclear weapons program?

449
00:31:30,321 --> 00:31:35,013
Do you know what 1% of the population
of this country is?

450
00:31:35,952 --> 00:31:39,914
It's 3,240,000 souls.

451
00:31:40,749 --> 00:31:45,858
Okay, sir. Look, we're not machines.
We look at the evidence. We game it out.

452
00:31:45,754 --> 00:31:48,882
And believe it or not, not everybody agrees
all the time.

453
00:31:48,778 --> 00:31:50,864
- It's a process.
- It's a process.

454
00:31:50,864 --> 00:31:52,845
- Yes.
- And not everyone agrees.

455
00:31:52,741 --> 00:31:53,888
Exactly.

456
00:31:56,077 --> 00:31:57,225
Who doesn't agree?

457
00:32:03,586 --> 00:32:06,401
What the hell is Joe Turner
doing next to the DCI?

458
00:32:06,401 --> 00:32:09,842
Didn't you hear? On Friday,
the DCI took him to the White House.

459
00:32:09,738 --> 00:32:12,241
He briefed the President
on aluminum tubes.

460
00:32:12,136 --> 00:32:13,596
You've got to be kidding me.

461
00:32:14,639 --> 00:32:15,995
That guy's a tool.

462
00:32:15,890 --> 00:32:18,810
Ready! Aim! Fire!

463
00:32:19,540 --> 00:32:22,147
It's a dead end.
So, you got a list of Iraqi scientists.

464
00:32:22,147 --> 00:32:23,920
How do you suggest we get to them?

465
00:32:23,920 --> 00:32:26,944
The Mukhabarat watch the scientists
night and day.

466
00:32:26,840 --> 00:32:28,404
Their houses are bugged,
their friends are followed.

467
00:32:28,300 --> 00:32:30,385
Send in
a team of NOCs by taxi from the north.

468
00:32:30,385 --> 00:32:32,471
Say you get through the checkpoints
and roadblocks.

469
00:32:32,366 --> 00:32:33,931
If you showed up in my bedroom
in the dead of night

470
00:32:33,931 --> 00:32:37,163
asking me to help out Uncle Sam,
I'm going to react unpredictably.

471
00:32:37,059 --> 00:32:39,145
Given the theater, it's all too high-risk.

472
00:32:39,145 --> 00:32:41,230
Even if we get to them,
they won't come out alone.

473
00:32:41,230 --> 00:32:43,316
They'll want to bring their family,
their children, their kids.

474
00:32:43,316 --> 00:32:45,818
We'll get down south to Basra,
we'll ask for Jordan's help.

475
00:32:45,714 --> 00:32:47,904
Give me two months.
I'll give you two or three.

476
00:32:47,904 --> 00:32:50,928
No, I have 29 names.
I need to get to them all.

477
00:32:50,928 --> 00:32:54,265
The wall's too high, Val.
What do you want to do, train a mouse?

478
00:32:54,161 --> 00:32:55,308
Maybe.

479
00:33:00,313 --> 00:33:03,337
Hey. Did I wake you?

480
00:33:10,115 --> 00:33:12,201
It's 3:45 in the morning.

481
00:33:13,035 --> 00:33:15,434
I got to be at the airport in 45 minutes.

482
00:33:16,893 --> 00:33:20,335
How long this time?
Do we need childcare tomorrow?

483
00:33:20,335 --> 00:33:22,107
I left it on a Post-it.

484
00:33:22,837 --> 00:33:24,714
Of course. It's on the Post-it.

485
00:33:25,861 --> 00:33:28,468
Look, I didn't want to wake you.

486
00:33:29,720 --> 00:33:32,952
All we've been doing is leaving Post-its
for each other for months.

487
00:33:33,682 --> 00:33:35,246
The fridge is like a dead letter drop.

488
00:33:42,337 --> 00:33:43,380
Shit.

489
00:33:44,110 --> 00:33:48,698
I sound like some old... God.

490
00:33:57,249 --> 00:33:58,918
I don't know where you go.

491
00:34:01,420 --> 00:34:04,653
I don't know who you meet.
I don't know if you're in jail somewhere

492
00:34:04,549 --> 00:34:07,051
or in a ditch somewhere in Jordan, Beirut.

493
00:34:10,597 --> 00:34:15,081
If you went missing, I couldn't tell anybody
because you were never there.

494
00:34:20,399 --> 00:34:21,755
I don't know where you go.

495
00:34:23,736 --> 00:34:25,300
I'm going to Cleveland.

496
00:34:28,950 --> 00:34:33,017
It's on the Post-it.

497
00:34:46,782 --> 00:34:48,242
Have a good day.

498
00:35:26,407 --> 00:35:27,867
You have two of these
in your luggage.

499
00:35:27,867 --> 00:35:29,327
This is the only pen we want you to use.

500
00:35:30,162 --> 00:35:32,873
The ink on this pen
is visible for 10 seconds.

501
00:35:32,873 --> 00:35:34,958
Only when given the correct
chemical fixative can it be read.

502
00:35:34,958 --> 00:35:38,400
If the Mukhabarat see any of this they will
do things to me that you cannot imagine.

503
00:35:39,234 --> 00:35:42,049
Tell me what you need to know.
I will memorize it.

504
00:35:42,049 --> 00:35:45,386
We have 50 very specific questions,
some extremely technical.

505
00:35:45,386 --> 00:35:48,202
You have 206 bones in your body.

506
00:35:48,723 --> 00:35:52,477
Do you want their names
in English, Latin or Arabic?

507
00:35:57,795 --> 00:35:58,942
How do you feel?

508
00:36:08,015 --> 00:36:11,560
If anyone stops you,
anyone asks you anything,

509
00:36:13,541 --> 00:36:15,940
stay calm. You're just visiting your brother.

510
00:36:16,566 --> 00:36:17,713
Keep it simple.

511
00:36:17,713 --> 00:36:19,381
How do you do it?

512
00:36:20,320 --> 00:36:22,197
Lie to someone to their face?

513
00:36:23,448 --> 00:36:24,595
Huh?

514
00:36:29,705 --> 00:36:33,771
You have to know why you're lying

515
00:36:34,710 --> 00:36:36,066
and never forget the truth.

516
00:36:44,304 --> 00:36:45,346
It's time.

517
00:36:49,205 --> 00:36:50,769
Are you ready?

518
00:37:15,274 --> 00:37:18,820
Welcome to Queen Alia
International Airport.

519
00:37:24,972 --> 00:37:28,309
The Mukhabarat is watching the flight desk
on this side.

520
00:37:54,796 --> 00:37:56,986
Based on what you know right now,

521
00:37:57,090 --> 00:38:00,114
how close
is Saddam Hussein's government...

522
00:38:00,010 --> 00:38:04,077
How close is that government
to developing a nuclear capability?

523
00:38:05,224 --> 00:38:09,082
You'll get different estimates
about precisely how close he is.

524
00:38:09,082 --> 00:38:12,106
We do know that there have been shipments

525
00:38:12,002 --> 00:38:15,652
going into Iraq, for instance,
of aluminum tubes

526
00:38:15,652 --> 00:38:19,614
that really are only suited
for nuclear weapons programs,

527
00:38:19,510 --> 00:38:21,074
centrifuge programs.

528
00:38:21,596 --> 00:38:24,828
There will always be some uncertainty

529
00:38:24,828 --> 00:38:28,061
about how quickly
he can acquire nuclear weapons.

530
00:38:28,061 --> 00:38:30,876
But we don't want the smoking gun
to be a mushroom cloud.

531
00:38:32,023 --> 00:38:33,796
It's a coordinated leak.

532
00:38:33,796 --> 00:38:36,403
Someone in the O VP leaked a story
to The New York Times.

533
00:38:36,403 --> 00:38:38,384
Now they're all across the networks
quoting the leak.

534
00:38:38,802 --> 00:38:41,826
"Smoking gun?" "Mushroom Cloud?"
They're using the same words.

535
00:38:42,139 --> 00:38:43,181
It's a coordinated leak.

536
00:38:43,181 --> 00:38:44,328
I'm coming home.

537
00:38:44,433 --> 00:38:46,101
We have been able to intercept
and prevent him

538
00:38:46,101 --> 00:38:48,291
from acquiring
through this particular channel

539
00:38:49,334 --> 00:38:52,775
the kinds of tubes
that are necessary to build a centrifuge.

540
00:38:53,192 --> 00:38:55,695
I always close the door,
I always roll up the window.

541
00:38:55,695 --> 00:38:56,946
Yeah, but you can smell it.

542
00:38:57,050 --> 00:38:58,927
What would you have me do, roll up a towel

543
00:38:58,823 --> 00:39:00,909
and hide in the room
like a teenager smoking?

544
00:39:00,909 --> 00:39:02,473
Or sandbag my study?

545
00:39:02,473 --> 00:39:05,601
- Just go out on the deck.
- It's minus 10 degrees outside.

546
00:39:06,018 --> 00:39:07,061
Steve, help me.

547
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:11,649
You're missing the whole point. A cigar,
you want the Winston Churchill vibe,

548
00:39:11,545 --> 00:39:14,048
the slippers, the crackling fire.

549
00:39:14,048 --> 00:39:16,863
Or musty books, like a faithful dog.

550
00:39:16,863 --> 00:39:19,470
You don't want to be outside
in a goose down freezing your balls off

551
00:39:19,470 --> 00:39:20,513
alone in the dark.

552
00:39:20,513 --> 00:39:23,641
So, don't think Churchill.
Think Scott of the Antarctic.

553
00:39:26,248 --> 00:39:27,291
I quit.

554
00:39:27,187 --> 00:39:29,377
Can I ask a dumb question?
What is an aluminum tube?

555
00:39:29,377 --> 00:39:33,652
It's a centrifuge. It enriches uranium.

556
00:39:33,652 --> 00:39:34,695
How?

557
00:39:34,695 --> 00:39:36,676
Nobody knows.

558
00:39:36,676 --> 00:39:38,866
They do know what they're for. Come on.

559
00:39:38,866 --> 00:39:41,056
Have you read about this, Valerie?

560
00:39:41,160 --> 00:39:43,454
Oh, I was away last week on business.

561
00:39:43,454 --> 00:39:46,478
Basically, Saddam bought these tubes
and we nailed him.

562
00:39:46,374 --> 00:39:48,355
We have them
and they're packed with uranium.

563
00:39:48,355 --> 00:39:49,503
They're packed with uranium?

564
00:39:49,503 --> 00:39:50,962
They're packed with uranium!

565
00:39:52,318 --> 00:39:53,778
My expert husband.

566
00:39:53,778 --> 00:39:57,011
Okay, right. So, they're for purifying,
but the bomb comes later.

567
00:39:57,011 --> 00:39:59,722
Basically, you boil it up
and you make the big one. Right?

568
00:39:59,618 --> 00:40:02,225
No, says who? It's a bunch of tubes, Jeff.

569
00:40:02,120 --> 00:40:04,102
Everything you read!
The New York Times. You're right.

570
00:40:04,102 --> 00:40:06,396
Joe, you know about this stuff.
What's your hunch on this?

571
00:40:06,396 --> 00:40:08,586
I don't know anything about tubes.
I'm not qualified.

572
00:40:08,586 --> 00:40:09,628
I think...

573
00:40:09,733 --> 00:40:14,321
It's a pretext! 50% of Americans
think Saddam blew up the towers.

574
00:40:14,217 --> 00:40:16,302
Yeah, but you can't say
he's not a threat!

575
00:40:16,302 --> 00:40:18,283
- I agree!
- Saddam's not a threat!

576
00:40:18,283 --> 00:40:19,535
Nobody's saying that.

577
00:40:19,639 --> 00:40:21,203
If we got rid of Hitler in the '30s...

578
00:40:21,203 --> 00:40:24,644
He's not Hitler! I'm sorry, he's not Hitler.
He's Saddam.

579
00:40:24,540 --> 00:40:29,754
We put him there. Why? It suited us!
He's our fault, always was. He's not a threat!

580
00:40:29,546 --> 00:40:31,735
Have you met him, Fred?
Have you met Saddam?

581
00:40:32,048 --> 00:40:35,072
Has Saddam looked you in the eye
and threatened you?

582
00:40:36,636 --> 00:40:37,888
Has he threatened to kill you?

583
00:40:39,765 --> 00:40:41,329
You don't know what you're talking about.

584
00:40:45,709 --> 00:40:49,150
- All right.
- I think that's probably true.

585
00:40:49,776 --> 00:40:52,174
I'm guilty of part of that.

586
00:40:52,174 --> 00:40:53,947
Dessert? Coffee? Any takers?

587
00:40:53,947 --> 00:40:56,137
- It was delicious.
- I do think he had a point.

588
00:40:56,137 --> 00:40:57,492
He's making a separate point.

589
00:40:57,492 --> 00:40:59,473
Obviously, this needs to go elsewhere.

590
00:41:01,038 --> 00:41:04,583
We have a rule in our house.
No politics at the table.

591
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:06,773
It always ends in a squabble.

592
00:41:07,190 --> 00:41:09,589
Nobody knows what's going on over there.

593
00:41:09,589 --> 00:41:11,674
At the end of the day, who really knows?

594
00:41:12,508 --> 00:41:15,950
That's right, Sue. Who knows?

595
00:41:54,324 --> 00:41:55,367
Hammad.

596
00:43:30,260 --> 00:43:31,512
Cuckoo!

597
00:44:01,544 --> 00:44:03,525
They have given me questions for you.

598
00:44:05,402 --> 00:44:06,966
What questions?

599
00:44:06,966 --> 00:44:11,972
How close is your program to a warhead?
When and where is the first test scheduled?

600
00:44:11,868 --> 00:44:14,475
How much 235-grade uranium do you have?

601
00:44:14,475 --> 00:44:19,584
Identify other scientists of the program.
Who in the military controls the program?

602
00:44:19,376 --> 00:44:22,087
Which of the... Which...

603
00:44:23,338 --> 00:44:24,590
What is it?

604
00:44:24,590 --> 00:44:26,675
- They don't know?
- What, Hammad?

605
00:44:27,197 --> 00:44:30,221
The program was completely destroyed
in the '90s.

606
00:44:30,221 --> 00:44:32,723
The Americans destroyed it.
They know this.

607
00:44:34,705 --> 00:44:35,852
What else?

608
00:44:38,146 --> 00:44:41,170
How advanced is the centrifuge facility?

609
00:44:41,170 --> 00:44:43,881
Which method are you using
to separate fissile isotopes?

610
00:44:43,777 --> 00:44:45,028
This is insane.

611
00:44:46,175 --> 00:44:48,469
We don't have the spare parts
to keep a tank on the road.

612
00:44:49,721 --> 00:44:53,683
I have to work at a plant
which develops fertilizer. They know.

613
00:44:57,750 --> 00:44:59,627
They know this. They must know.

614
00:45:04,111 --> 00:45:05,675
You need to see this.

615
00:45:10,785 --> 00:45:13,288
We need to get Jack to see this, and Bill.

616
00:45:14,852 --> 00:45:17,563
Ambassador Wilson
was the last American official

617
00:45:17,563 --> 00:45:19,753
to meet with Saddam Hussein.

618
00:45:19,753 --> 00:45:22,569
It was 1990, and it was a pretty scary time.

619
00:45:23,194 --> 00:45:26,010
Saddam threatened
that he was going to execute

620
00:45:25,905 --> 00:45:29,764
anybody sheltering
people he called foreigners.

621
00:45:29,764 --> 00:45:31,745
Ambassador Wilson
called a press conference

622
00:45:31,641 --> 00:45:33,726
and appeared with a noose around his neck.

623
00:45:34,978 --> 00:45:37,272
And he said, the press reports,

624
00:45:37,272 --> 00:45:41,234
"If the choice is to allow Americans
to be taken as hostages

625
00:45:41,026 --> 00:45:44,884
"or to be executed,
I'll bring my own fucking rope."

626
00:45:46,344 --> 00:45:48,221
Saddam backed down

627
00:45:48,221 --> 00:45:51,871
and Ambassador Wilson
helped thousands get safely home.

628
00:45:51,871 --> 00:45:54,061
When he himself came home
to the United States

629
00:45:54,061 --> 00:45:56,563
he was warmly greeted by our President,

630
00:45:56,563 --> 00:46:00,526
who took him to the Oval Office
and introduced him to the War Cabinet

631
00:46:00,422 --> 00:46:02,194
as an American hero.

632
00:46:03,759 --> 00:46:07,304
That's not quite right. It was
the Roosevelt Room, not the Oval Office.

633
00:46:10,641 --> 00:46:11,788
In the middle, please?

634
00:46:11,788 --> 00:46:14,708
Does Saddam pose an imminent threat
to national security?

635
00:46:15,646 --> 00:46:19,713
Zahraa's brother worked with
500 nuclear scientists at the Safa factory.

636
00:46:19,817 --> 00:46:22,842
In '91 it was blanket-bombed by B-52's.

637
00:46:22,842 --> 00:46:25,449
Hussein Kamel kept the scientists together,

638
00:46:25,449 --> 00:46:27,117
threatening to kill them
if they tried to leave.

639
00:46:27,117 --> 00:46:29,307
But sanctions destroyed the economy.

640
00:46:29,307 --> 00:46:33,582
And when Kamel was executed in '95,
the team just drifted apart.

641
00:46:33,895 --> 00:46:36,502
They're all saying the same thing. Everyone.

642
00:46:36,711 --> 00:46:37,962
There's no weapons program.

643
00:46:38,692 --> 00:46:42,237
You've got 30 nuclear scientists
interrogated by Iraqis in Iraq

644
00:46:42,133 --> 00:46:43,280
all saying the same thing.

645
00:46:43,280 --> 00:46:46,513
Jim, these people took a great risk.

646
00:46:46,409 --> 00:46:49,120
To bring us what?
I could have saved us the airfare.

647
00:46:49,120 --> 00:46:51,205
The White House is getting stove-piped.

648
00:46:52,144 --> 00:46:56,419
Someone is cherry-picking raw data
and serving it up to the press as fact.

649
00:46:56,315 --> 00:46:59,339
Then they look to us to confirm it.
It's bullshit.

650
00:46:59,339 --> 00:47:01,425
One of Saddam's ministers asked him

651
00:47:01,320 --> 00:47:05,909
why he had executed a certain official
who'd been a loyal supporter.

652
00:47:07,369 --> 00:47:11,748
Saddam said,
"I would rather kill my friends in error

653
00:47:13,625 --> 00:47:15,919
"than to allow my enemies to live."

654
00:47:17,066 --> 00:47:18,943
For me, that's the mark of a monster.

655
00:47:21,759 --> 00:47:26,139
Vice President Cheney,
members of Congress,

656
00:47:26,139 --> 00:47:28,954
distinguished citizens and fellow citizens.

657
00:47:29,371 --> 00:47:31,457
Every year, by law and by custom

658
00:47:31,457 --> 00:47:34,481
we meet here
to consider the state of the Union.

659
00:47:34,794 --> 00:47:36,775
- Thank you so much.
- You're welcome.

660
00:47:38,235 --> 00:47:41,155
Wait, we'd like you to have this coffee mug

661
00:47:41,051 --> 00:47:42,928
- and some pennants for your kids.
- Thank you.

662
00:47:43,032 --> 00:47:45,535
Thank you so much for coming
and speaking to us.

663
00:47:45,535 --> 00:47:46,682
Drive safe out there.

664
00:47:46,682 --> 00:47:48,976
...the gravest danger in the War on Terror.

665
00:47:48,976 --> 00:47:51,374
The gravest danger
facing America and the world.

666
00:47:53,147 --> 00:47:54,607
I'll have a black eye to go, please.

667
00:47:54,607 --> 00:47:55,754
What's that?

668
00:47:55,754 --> 00:47:57,944
Two shots of espresso in coffee.
Black coffee.

669
00:48:01,489 --> 00:48:06,912
US Intelligence indicates Saddam Hussein
has upwards of 30,000 munitions capable

670
00:48:06,912 --> 00:48:08,789
- of delivering chemical agents.
- Thank you.

671
00:48:11,604 --> 00:48:15,150
From three Iraqi defectors
we know that Iraq in the late 1990s

672
00:48:15,045 --> 00:48:17,861
had several mobile
biological weapons labs.

673
00:48:22,241 --> 00:48:26,412
Saddam Hussein had an advanced
nuclear weapons development program,

674
00:48:28,289 --> 00:48:30,374
had a design for a nuclear weapon,

675
00:48:31,417 --> 00:48:35,484
and was working on five different methods
of enriching uranium for a bomb.

676
00:48:36,944 --> 00:48:39,029
The British government has learned
that Saddam Hussein

677
00:48:39,134 --> 00:48:43,618
recently sought significant quantities
of uranium from Africa.

678
00:48:46,433 --> 00:48:49,040
Our intelligence sources tell us
that he has attempted to purchase

679
00:48:48,936 --> 00:48:53,628
high-strength aluminum tubes
suitable for nuclear weapons production.

680
00:48:55,297 --> 00:49:00,094
This nation fights reluctantly
because we know the cost.

681
00:48:59,885 --> 00:49:02,284
We dread the days of mourning
that always come.

682
00:49:03,639 --> 00:49:05,099
We seek peace.

683
00:49:06,038 --> 00:49:07,706
We strive for peace.

684
00:49:08,645 --> 00:49:12,190
And sometimes peace must be defended.

685
00:49:13,754 --> 00:49:14,901
In Baghdad,

686
00:49:15,006 --> 00:49:19,072
42 cruise missiles and bunker buster bombs
from F-117's

687
00:49:18,968 --> 00:49:20,741
were aimed at Iraq's leaders.

688
00:49:20,637 --> 00:49:21,888
...campaign called Shock and Awe.

689
00:49:21,992 --> 00:49:25,225
He vowed the US
will accept no outcome but victory.

690
00:49:35,444 --> 00:49:38,051
For approximately five to eight minutes.

691
00:51:30,568 --> 00:51:31,819
Bill? Wait up.

692
00:51:31,819 --> 00:51:34,739
Every team is combing the desert
looking for WMDs.

693
00:51:34,635 --> 00:51:35,886
Look, all I need is a couple...

694
00:51:35,990 --> 00:51:37,972
We don't have the resources, Val!

695
00:51:37,972 --> 00:51:39,744
- To get these families...
- Listen to me!

696
00:51:39,640 --> 00:51:43,081
Will you listen to me?
Let's say we extract these guys.

697
00:51:43,081 --> 00:51:44,437
We bring them home and put them on CNN.

698
00:51:44,437 --> 00:51:47,774
What do you think they're going to tell us
that the White House wants to hear? Huh?

699
00:51:47,670 --> 00:51:50,485
"Thank you, and by the way,
there was no nuclear program.

700
00:51:50,485 --> 00:51:53,509
"There is no WMD. P.S. You all knew that."

701
00:51:54,969 --> 00:51:56,533
Think about it.
Do you want me to go to the DCI

702
00:51:56,533 --> 00:51:57,785
and ask him to sign off on his own funeral?

703
00:51:57,785 --> 00:51:59,453
Bill, I gave my word.

704
00:51:59,349 --> 00:52:01,747
That's not my problem.
I got bigger problems.

705
00:52:08,630 --> 00:52:11,341
It's like if there was a baby
on the ledge up on 7th.

706
00:52:11,341 --> 00:52:14,261
No one would get up and save it
in case the White House wanted it there.

707
00:52:14,261 --> 00:52:18,745
Bill's right. This is just one snafu in 1,000
that we have right now.

708
00:52:18,536 --> 00:52:21,664
- These scientists are not our...
- These scientists are the WMD.

709
00:52:21,664 --> 00:52:25,210
If we can't protect them, they'll run straight
to the first country who can

710
00:52:25,106 --> 00:52:26,357
and they'll put them to work.

711
00:52:35,012 --> 00:52:38,662
I never said this.
If anyone ever asks I'll deny all knowledge.

712
00:52:41,582 --> 00:52:43,250
How quietly can you do this?

713
00:54:09,071 --> 00:54:11,261
I need to know my family will be safe.

714
00:54:11,261 --> 00:54:13,034
My wife, my children, we're all in danger.

715
00:54:13,868 --> 00:54:15,328
Hammad, I know that.

716
00:54:15,432 --> 00:54:19,291
We'll take care of your family
but we have to move fast, okay?

717
00:54:19,186 --> 00:54:20,751
How do I know I can trust you?

718
00:54:20,855 --> 00:54:26,382
Hammad, listen to me, do exactly as I say.
We won't let you down.

719
00:54:30,136 --> 00:54:31,491
The US Military has reported

720
00:54:31,387 --> 00:54:35,141
the death of another five US soldiers
on Wednesday.

721
00:54:35,141 --> 00:54:39,312
One soldier died after being struck
by a bomb while on foot patrol.

722
00:54:39,208 --> 00:54:41,398
Reported killed across the country.

723
00:54:41,398 --> 00:54:44,839
Official Iraqi figures show that 966...

724
00:54:45,569 --> 00:54:48,802
The British government has learned
that Saddam Hussein...

725
00:54:48,802 --> 00:54:50,574
...significant quantities of uranium

726
00:54:51,096 --> 00:54:52,243
from Africa.

727
00:54:54,641 --> 00:54:56,622
The British government has learned
that Saddam Hussein

728
00:54:56,518 --> 00:55:01,106
recently sought significant quantities
of uranium from Africa.

729
00:55:01,836 --> 00:55:04,548
Listen, Pete, I want to ask you
something. It's very important.

730
00:55:05,590 --> 00:55:10,492
Is it possible that the President is referring
to another African country, not Niger?

731
00:55:11,534 --> 00:55:13,411
I've seen the INR. It's Niger.

732
00:55:14,141 --> 00:55:16,435
He's referring specifically
to yellowcake from Niger. Why?

733
00:55:20,502 --> 00:55:24,778
I'm the source. I went to Niger. It's wrong.
It's not true.

734
00:55:25,612 --> 00:55:26,863
I see.

735
00:55:29,053 --> 00:55:30,930
What exactly are you proposing to do?

736
00:55:33,016 --> 00:55:34,476
I don't know what I'm gonna do.

737
00:55:35,101 --> 00:55:36,248
Do you want my advice?

738
00:55:36,353 --> 00:55:38,751
Do nothing. You already did your job.

739
00:55:38,751 --> 00:55:41,567
You did your best, you came home.
End of story.

740
00:55:42,401 --> 00:55:45,738
We're talking about Niger.
Yellowcake from Niger.

741
00:55:45,633 --> 00:55:49,075
I don't have to go all the way to Africa
to know something's messed up here.

742
00:55:49,492 --> 00:55:50,743
Three months and what have we found?

743
00:55:51,264 --> 00:55:55,227
No centrifuges, no yellowcake,
no bio, no WMDs.

744
00:55:55,436 --> 00:55:57,417
You think something's up, here?
Join the line.

745
00:55:57,521 --> 00:55:59,607
It stretches all the way from State
to the Pentagon and back.

746
00:55:59,502 --> 00:56:01,484
Why hasn't anybody stepped forward?

747
00:56:01,379 --> 00:56:02,735
Why do you think, Joe?

748
00:56:03,882 --> 00:56:05,446
We went to war.

749
00:56:05,759 --> 00:56:08,262
Listen, as your friend now,

750
00:56:09,409 --> 00:56:12,746
just be smart.

751
00:56:12,642 --> 00:56:14,623
You have a wife and a family.

752
00:56:15,040 --> 00:56:18,064
We're talking
about the President of the United States.

753
00:56:17,960 --> 00:56:19,524
The White House.

754
00:56:19,524 --> 00:56:22,339
Go take a long look in the mirror
and say that again.

755
00:56:38,920 --> 00:56:40,171
What's wrong?

756
00:56:40,797 --> 00:56:42,152
Nothing.

757
00:56:43,821 --> 00:56:44,864
I'm just tired.

758
00:56:45,698 --> 00:56:47,366
Are the kids asleep?

759
00:56:47,366 --> 00:56:48,722
Yeah, they're asleep.

760
00:56:49,139 --> 00:56:50,286
Okay, good.

761
00:56:52,789 --> 00:56:54,040
I'm gonna go up.

762
00:57:01,131 --> 00:57:05,615
There are some who feel like
the conditions are such

763
00:57:05,615 --> 00:57:07,388
that they can attack us there.

764
00:57:07,388 --> 00:57:08,743
My answer is, bring them on.

765
00:57:09,369 --> 00:57:13,332
We've got the force necessary
to deal with the security situation.

766
00:57:59,319 --> 00:58:03,490
There's zero, nada, nothing new here.

767
00:58:03,490 --> 00:58:05,888
I think the President's statement
at the State of the Union

768
00:58:05,784 --> 00:58:07,557
goes much broader than the Niger question.

769
00:58:07,557 --> 00:58:10,998
Is the President's statement correct?

770
00:58:10,894 --> 00:58:14,022
Yes.
I see nothing that goes broader

771
00:58:13,813 --> 00:58:18,089
that would indicate there was no basis
for the President's broader statement.

772
00:58:18,089 --> 00:58:22,156
But, specifically on the yellowcake
from Niger,

773
00:58:22,051 --> 00:58:24,763
we have acknowledged that that did in fact

774
00:58:24,763 --> 00:58:26,223
turn out to be a forgery.

775
00:58:26,744 --> 00:58:27,787
Oh, shit.

776
00:58:27,891 --> 00:58:28,934
I'm sorry?

777
00:58:28,934 --> 00:58:29,977
The British report.

778
00:58:31,958 --> 00:58:33,105
Um...

779
00:58:33,313 --> 00:58:34,773
Mark, clear my morning.

780
00:58:36,025 --> 00:58:37,068
It was wrong, then?

781
00:58:37,172 --> 00:58:42,073
Let me do this, David.
On David's specific question.

782
00:58:41,864 --> 00:58:44,158
I'm going to come back to you on that.

783
00:58:45,306 --> 00:58:46,453
Fleischer plowed the briefing.

784
00:58:46,453 --> 00:58:47,495
I saw.

785
00:58:47,495 --> 00:58:50,937
CBS knows yellowcake was pulled
from Cincinnati 10 weeks ago.

786
00:58:50,937 --> 00:58:52,292
At the CIA's request.

787
00:58:52,188 --> 00:58:54,273
They also had
that Gerson wrote both speeches.

788
00:58:54,273 --> 00:58:55,942
Karl is looking for you. He's unhappy.

789
00:58:55,942 --> 00:58:58,445
I want a transcript of everything across

790
00:58:58,445 --> 00:59:03,450
